{"id": "general_lmsys_chat_1m_2300_837439", "question": "Explain Streaming responses in FastAPI", "answer": "Streaming responses in FastAPI refer to a technique where the server sends the response data to the client in smaller chunks, instead of sending it all at once. This can be useful when working with large files, real-time data or long-running processes, where it's not efficient or feasible to load the entire response into memory before sending it to the client.\n\nFastAPI provides built-in support for streaming responses using the `StreamingResponse` class from the `fastapi.responses` module. Here's a basic example of how to use streaming responses in FastAPI:\n\n```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nfrom fastapi.responses import StreamingResponse\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\ndef generate_data():\n    for i in range(100):\n        yield f\"data chunk {i}\\n\"\n\n@app.get(\"/streaming\")\nasync def stream_data():\n    return StreamingResponse(generate_data(), media_type=\"text/plain\")\n```\n\nIn this example, the `generate_data` function is a generator that yields data chunks. The `stream_data` route returns a `StreamingResponse` object that takes the generator as input, along with the media type of the response.\n\nWhen a client requests the `/streaming` route, FastAPI will start sending the data chunks one by one, as they are generated by the `generate_data` function. The client will receive the data incrementally, without having to wait for the entire response to be generated.\n\nStreaming responses can be used with various types of data, such as text, JSON, or binary data, by adapting the generator function and setting the appropriate media type for the `StreamingResponse`."}
