{"id": "general_lmsys_chat_1m_2300_259229", "question": "What is learned helplessness among humans?", "answer": "Learned helplessness is a psychological state in which an individual feels like they have no control over the events that affect them. This feeling of powerlessness can lead to a variety of negative emotions, such as hopelessness, depression, and anxiety.\n\nLearned helplessness can occur when an individual experiences a series of uncontrollable events, or when they are repeatedly subjected to situations where they are unable to affect the outcome. For example, if someone is repeatedly subjected to electric shocks that they cannot prevent, they may eventually come to believe that they have no control over the situation and that their efforts to avoid the shocks are futile.\n\nLearned helplessness can have negative consequences for an individual's mental and physical health. It can lead to a loss of motivation, a decrease in self-esteem, and even physical health problems, such as increased stress levels and a weakened immune system.\n\nIt is important to note that learned helplessness is not an inherent or permanent condition. With therapy and other interventions, individuals can learn to overcome feelings of helplessness and regain a sense of control over their lives."}
